		<table width="90%" bgcolor="" style="border-collapse: collapse; border-left-width:1; border-right-width: 1; border-top-style: solid; border-left-style: solid; border-right-style: solid; border-bottom-style: solid; border-top-width: 1; border-bottom-width: 1" bordercolor="#FFFFFF" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" ID="Table2">  
		<tr>
			<td align="left" valign="top" background="/images/necrotableheader2.gif">
				<font width="100%" face="verdana" size="1" color=white><b>How to create a necromancer</b>
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr bgcolor="#ffebdc">
			<td align="left" valign="top" valign="top">
				<font face="verdana" size="1" color=white>
				written by <b>Kusotare</b> on <b>3/21/2003 8:25:17 AM</b>
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr bgcolor="#37437B">
			<td align="left" valign="top" valign="top">
				<font face="verdana" size="1" color=white><blockquote><br>
				Now, if you did NOT know it before, you should put 25 points in int.<br><br>This is preferred for all int casters, especially necros. However, this is all-important for Iksar and others with lower int. I'm not saying you SHOULDN'T play an Iksar. After all, that's my favorite to play, I'm just saying it'll be a little harder before you can max your int.<br><br>So where do the other five points go?<br><br>WELL! As a necromancer, you need spells. Nearly as high as you can imagine, you'll need to buy spells. You also have pets that will melee for you, even if you can't find a group. Therefore, physical prowess is not always needed. I recommend the other five points in charisma, as you'll need it to purchase the 20+p spells.<br><br>Now we get to the skills. You should start with a couple of points in piercing. Two, to be exact. Then move on to one in 1hb or in 2hb, whichever you think you'll use more. I prefer 1hb, because it lets me carry other things in my off-hand. Since you'll be using alteration for your lifetap abilities, you should put two in there.<br><br>Now, I write this as though you have PoP or made an Iksar. If you chose another, then you'll have to hunt in the newbie areas on your own. If you ARE an Iksar, you can get money for your first level spells easily. Talk to the guy in the Haggle Baron's manor (across from the monk guild). He'll give you a sack to fill with 8 scaled curskins.<br><br>Do so. They drop off of Scaled Wolf Pups and Cubs. Pups are the ones you should try.<br><br>Once you get them, combine them in the bag, and you got yourself a completed quest... once you turn it in. He'll then give you a piece of his special curskin armor that's so wonderful, everyone will want to wear it!<br><br>But you can't.<br><br>You can, however, sell it back to him for a few gold. Remember-your spells are only 1 gold or so at this level, so you can afford some now. I recommend Siphon Strength and Cavorting Bones.<br><br>After level 4, once you get lifespike, Leering Corpse, Clinging Darkness, and Poison Bolt, go to the Lake of Ill Omen. (If you aren't an Iksar, be careful of the guards!) Here, you can kill just about anything near the guards to the first outhouses. Do so, focusing on the skellies. If you loot a Rusty or Tarnished Shan'tok from one, give it to your pet. It increases the damage and, apparently, how often it hits.<br><br>That's all. I know I went a bit past creation, but level 4, to me, is still in the creation process.<br><br>P.S. Survival Staves are 1hb. They are also cheap. Pick one up, eh?<br>&nbsp;<br>
			</td>
		</tr>
